#show: main.with(
  title: "What My Best Answer Could Not See",
  desc: "What Participatory Design taught me about uncertainty, care, and what even a well-reasoned answer can miss.",
  date: "2026-07-16",
  tags: ("participatory-design", "reflection"),
)

Among the many ways I understand myself, I have long seen myself as a system builder.

I am used to breaking problems into smaller parts, comparing possible approaches, and looking for the best answer under a given set of constraints. Which method is faster? Which one is more accurate? Which architecture is more reliable when something goes wrong?

This way of thinking has shaped how I work as both an engineer and a researcher. It is useful, and I still trust it. But without noticing, I also brought the same habit into human problems. I assumed that if I observed a situation carefully enough, it would eventually become clear. There would be better answers and worse answers. If I had not found the right one, I probably had not understood the problem well enough.

I wanted to be able to say: this is good, and that is bad.

Participatory Design was not a single turning point for me. But after working on a few PD research projects, I began to notice that the world did not always fit so neatly into this way of thinking.

== What PD made visible

Participatory Design, or PD, is a way of designing with the people who will live with the consequences of a system.

At first, I approached PD much as I approached engineering. I saw it as another way to find a better answer. I could speak with people, discover needs I had missed, and improve the design. More perspectives would give me a more complete picture, and a more complete picture would lead to a better solution.

Instead, the picture became more complicated.

A feature that looked helpful to me created more work for someone else. Giving one person more freedom placed more responsibility on another. A rule meant to protect someone also narrowed that person's choices, even when those choices involved real risk.

At first, I thought we were looking at the same problem from different angles. Over time, I realized that we were often trying to protect different things.

I wanted the system to be clearer and more efficient. Someone else wanted to reduce the chance of an accident. Another person wanted to keep the right to make decisions about their own life. Someone else was thinking about who might be hurt by those decisions.

They were not simply protecting themselves. Often, they were also thinking about the people who depended on them. A choice that put their own job, health, or safety at risk could reach far beyond them.

The difficulty was that their care did not always point in the same direction.

Giving someone more freedom may require accepting more risk. Trying to remove that risk may take away part of that person's freedom. Sometimes every available choice seems to leave someone behind.

From the outside, hesitation can look like indecision. Sometimes that criticism is fair. Waiting can cause harm, and eventually someone may have to decide.

But hesitation is not always a lack of courage.

Sometimes a person pauses because they do not want to abandon either side. They want to protect someone, but they are afraid that doing so will hurt someone else. What looks like indecision from a distance may be a moment of care seen up close.

A good intention does not make a decision right. Yet I have become slower to reduce hesitation to weakness.

Before asking why someone failed to decide quickly, I try to ask what they were trying not to lose.

== What my answer could not see

Each time I worked on a PD project, I was struck by how many reasonable ways there were to understand the same situation.

From where I stood, something could look plainly wrong. From another person's position, I could see that they had very few choices left. A useful feature for a researcher could become another task for a frontline worker. A convenient process for one person could create more checking and responsibility for another.

A decision that looked careless from one side could look almost unavoidable from the other.

Understanding the circumstances does not make a harmful decision harmless. The person who was hurt is still hurt. But calling one person bad is often not enough to explain how the harm came to be.

A person's actions carry more than the action itself. They also carry the responsibilities that person held, the risks they could see, the information they did not have, and the choices that were actually available to them.

Most of the time, we see only one scene.

But a person is larger than a single scene. One decision cannot explain an entire life.

The answers people brought into PD sessions were often different from the one I had imagined. It was not because they had misunderstood the problem. They could see things I could not, and they were responsible for things I did not have to carry.

I was thinking about whether the system worked well. A person in the field was thinking about what would happen when it failed. One person cared most about the freedom to choose. Another was thinking about who might be harmed by that choice.

Each position made sense on its own.

Everyone was describing a kind of best answer, but those answers did not always fit together. I had thought of “the best” as a single point, the answer we would reach after enough analysis. PD showed me that people can act carefully and generously, yet still arrive at incompatible conclusions.

My task was not always to lead everyone toward the answer I had already found.

Sometimes my task was to ask what my answer had failed to see.

== PD was not about producing agreement

This idea is not new to Participatory Design. A simple principle runs through its history:

#blockquote[
“Those affected by a design should have a say in the design process.”
]

The point is not that everyone must eventually agree. Early PD treated participation as more than feedback, and conflict as more than a failure to communicate. People affected by a system were meant to help shape it, even when their needs did not neatly align.
#footnote[
Pelle Ehn, “Participation in Design Things,” 2008.
#link("https://www.diva-portal.org/smash/get/diva2%3A1408103/FULLTEXT01.pdf")[PDF]
]

In early projects such as UTOPIA, workers did not participate only by reviewing a finished system. They worked with researchers through mock-ups and prototypes, using concrete objects to discuss how technology might change their skills, responsibilities, and daily work.
#footnote[
See the retrospective account of the UTOPIA project:
#link("https://www.lri.fr/~mbl/ENS/DEA-IHM/papers/Utopia.pdf")[“UTOPIA: Participatory Design from Scandinavia to the World”].
]

A prototype, in this sense, is not only a small version of an answer. It can also make disagreement visible.

Safety, autonomy, efficiency, and care are easy to support in the abstract. Once they become part of a workflow or interface, they begin to collide. More safety may require more monitoring. More autonomy may require accepting more risk.

When these conflicts appear, PD has not necessarily failed. It may mean that people and consequences that were previously invisible have finally entered the room.

For me, PD is not a method for making everyone happy. It is a practice of trying not to erase people while making a decision.

== “The least bad option” was too small a phrase

Eventually, a decision still has to be made. There may be no perfect answer, and every available option may create some kind of loss. We often describe such a decision as choosing the least bad option.

The phrase is not wrong. It is simply too thin.

It describes the visible result: one imperfect option was selected over another. It says little about the work that came before it.

People may have spent a long time trying to understand lives different from their own. They may have searched for a way to protect one person without hurting another. They may have asked who had been left out, and who would carry the cost.

Those efforts may still fail to protect everyone.

From the outside, the result may be called good, bad, or merely the least bad. But that judgment captures only one face of the process. The real work was trying to understand different fears and hopes without discarding any of them too easily.

It was also the painful recognition that even after everyone had tried, someone might still be hurt.

A caring process does not excuse a harmful result. It means the work cannot end when the decision is made. We still have to ask who was hurt, listen to people we failed to see, and change the decision when it proves wrong.

For me, PD is not primarily a way to select the least bad answer.

It is a way to remember the people who remain after the answer has been chosen.

== Learning to look a little longer

I used to think that simplifying complexity was one of a researcher's most important jobs.

I still believe that, to some extent. Research requires us to define a scope, choose variables, and build models that leave some details out. Without simplification, it would be difficult to understand a problem or build anything new.

But I no longer want to mistake the simplicity of a model for the shape of the world itself.

Something left out of a model does not become unimportant in real life. A cost that a system does not measure is still paid by someone. A number can improve while a person's work becomes harder.

Perhaps the world was not complicated because I had failed to solve it.

Perhaps part of the problem was my desire to make it fit into a single answer.

Complexity is not always a bug waiting to be removed. It may simply be what it looks like when many people are trying to live together.

Accepting that complexity does not mean refusing to judge. It does not mean every position is equally right, or that we should avoid making decisions. We still have to choose. Harm still requires responsibility.

It only means that, before we decide, we can look a little longer.

What was this person trying to protect? What could they see from where they stood? What choices were actually available to them?

These questions are not meant to excuse harm. They help us understand more precisely what went wrong. They keep us from ending the story with one person to blame.

I will never understand another person's life completely. No matter how carefully I listen, something will remain outside my view.

But the limits of my understanding do not give me permission to judge someone carelessly.

PD did not teach me to give up on finding good answers. It taught me to hold my own answer with a little more humility.

I can keep searching for what I believe is best while leaving room for someone else's best to exist. I can refuse to reduce a person to one choice. I can make a decision and still look back at the people who were left outside it.

I may never see the whole world.

But I can learn to look a little longer.

I now think that is part of building better systems, and part of seeing the world as it is, not only as I expect it to be.
